<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="599" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[812,1457,1181,1338]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">DIAGNOSIS. — Antenna entirely yellow, flagellomeres each with one prominent dorsal seta. Wing hyaline; Sc ends at C. Thorax, mid and hind coxa brown; fore coxa yellow. Abdominal segment 1 completely pale-yellow; segments 2-5 with a pale-yellow posterior band; gonostyli of subequal width along their entire course; aedeagus membranous.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[813,1414,1361,1385]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[813,1414,1361,1385]" box="[813,1414,1361,1385]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">
ETYMOLOGY. — The species epithet refers to the 
<typeStatus box="[1290,1332,1361,1385]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="600" pageId="8" pageNumber="599" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[813,1279,1428,1517]" box="[813,957,1428,1454]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[813,1279,1428,1517]" box="[813,866,1459,1485]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis box="[813,866,1459,1485]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[813,1279,1428,1517]" box="[813,1279,1490,1517]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,1027,1490,1516]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">General coloration.</emphasis>
Dark brown (
<figureCitation box="[1182,1265,1491,1517]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[132,143,891,909]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,214,840]" captionTargetId="figure-421@4.[132,1455,203,863]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Habitus of new species of Lygistorrhina (Probolaeus) Williston,1896:A, Lygistorrhina maculipennis n. sp., with detached head in separate box; paratype MHNH-ED-ED10673; B, Lygistorrhina conica n. sp., paratype NMS-10003795; C, Lygistorrhina mitarakensis n. sp., paratype NMS-10003799. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4321224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4321224/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[813,1115,1554,1581]" box="[813,1115,1554,1581]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,980,1555,1581]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">Measurements.</emphasis>
See 
<tableCitation box="[1029,1108,1554,1581]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[337,348,218,236]" captionTargetBox="[134,1453,294,711]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 1. — Measurements (length, in millimetres) for new species of Lygistorrhina (Probolaeus) Williston, 1896." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF15667E743B541BFEA7FF40FB09FF79" pageId="8" pageNumber="599" tableUuid="DF15667E743B541BFEA7FF40FB09FF79">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[810,1457,1618,2028]" lastBlockId="9.[130,776,215,369]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="600" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,878,1618,1644]" pageId="8" pageNumber="599">Head.</emphasis>
Rounded, dichoptic. Eyes appear larger than head height, with vertex appearing slightly depressed. Rounded ommatidia with similar diameter, interocular setae subequal in length to ommatidial diameter.Three ocelli arranged almost on a straight line, semi-circular, with median ocellus 1/3× the size of lateral ocelli. Antenna yellow, strongly tapering, shorter than hind femur, with length 
<quantity box="[1022,1154,1810,1836]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="599" unit="mm" value="0.85" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.8">0.8-0.9 mm</quantity>
; 14 flagellomeres, each with one strong dorsal seta, subcylindrical, gradually tapering; flagellomeres 1-9 1.5-2× as long as wide, flagellomeres 10-14 2-4× as long as wide. Face longer than wide. Clypeus with rounded apex, setose.Palpus length 
<quantity box="[1082,1166,1937,1964]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="599" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
, tapering towards apex, with a simple row of very long setae (at least 5× as long as palpus width). Hypopharynx length 
<quantity box="[1117,1200,2001,2028]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="599" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5mm</quantity>
; labellum slightly longer. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,216,215,241]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">Thorax.</emphasis>
Thorax completely brown. Scutum irregularly setose. Scutellum rounded, with 6 posterior setae. Antepronotum and proepisternum with 4-5 setae each. Laterotergite lobed, with one row of 14-20 setae. Hind coxa slightly longer than both metepimeron and laterotergite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[131,776,406,688]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,191,407,433]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">Legs.</emphasis>
Fore coxa pale-yellow; mid and hind coxa completely dark brown. Remainder of fore and mid legs yellow; hind femur pale-yellow basally, dark brown in distal 1/3; hind tibia brown in distal 1/4; hind tarsus entirely brown. Tibiae irregularly setose. Dorsal setae of hind tibia longer than tibial width. Fore basitarsus 1 shorter than fore tibia. Claws of fore and mid leg curved, apically blunt, with a small incision at apex; claw of hind legs setiform, straight and pointed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[130,777,725,1007]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[133,295,725,751]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">
Wing (
<figureCitation box="[207,287,725,751]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[132,143,891,909]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,214,840]" captionTargetId="figure-421@4.[132,1455,203,863]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Habitus of new species of Lygistorrhina (Probolaeus) Williston,1896:A, Lygistorrhina maculipennis n. sp., with detached head in separate box; paratype MHNH-ED-ED10673; B, Lygistorrhina conica n. sp., paratype NMS-10003795; C, Lygistorrhina mitarakensis n. sp., paratype NMS-10003799. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4321224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4321224/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
. Membrane hyaline, densely covered with microtrichia.Sc relatively long, ending on C; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[581,591,770,787]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">1</subScript>
slightly proximad the level of CuA tip; C extending to half the distance between tips of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[225,235,834,851]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">5</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[315,325,834,851]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">1</subScript>
; C, R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[391,401,834,851]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">1</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[473,483,834,851]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">5</subScript>
with dark setae, rest of the veins bare; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[279,289,866,883]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">1</subScript>
longer than M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[453,463,866,883]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">2</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[544,573,866,883]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">3+4</subScript>
, latter subequal in length. M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[241,251,898,915]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">1</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[333,343,898,915]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">2</subScript>
almost straight; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[552,582,898,915]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">3+4</subScript>
curved anteriorly and slightly sinuous; CuA curved posteriorly, sometimes inconspicuously sinusoid. Anal lobe well developed. Halter yellow, with the same length as first abdominal segment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[132,777,1044,1198]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,248,1044,1070]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Mainly dark brown. Segment 1 completely pale; segments 2-5 with pale-yellow posterior band, occupying 20-30% of segment length; segments 6 and 7 and terminalia dark brown (sometimes sternite 6 with inconspicuous pale apical spot).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[130,777,1235,1549]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,478,1235,1262]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">
Terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[270,387,1235,1262]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[132,143,1361,1379]" captionTargetBox="[132,1449,232,1318]" captionTargetId="figure-413@6.[121,1467,224,1329]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 3. — Male genitalia of new species of Lygistorrhina (Probolaeus) Williston, 1896: A, B, Lygistorrhina maculipennis n. sp., holotype MNHN-ED-ED10672; C, D, Lygistorrhina conica n. sp., holotype MNHN-ED-ED10674; E, F, Lygistorrhina mitarakensis n. sp., MNHN-ED-ED10691; A, C, E, dorsal view; B, D, F, ventral view. Scale bar: 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4321230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4321230/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">Figs 3E, F</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[403,465,1235,1262]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[132,143,1067,1085]" captionTargetBox="[131,1453,214,1024]" captionTargetId="figure-525@8.[131,1454,214,1027]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 4. — Aedeagal complex of new species of Lygistorrhina (Probolaeus) Williston, 1896: A, B, Lygistorrhina maculipennis n. sp., holotype MNHN-ED-ED10672; C, D, Lygistorrhina conica n. sp., holotype MNHN-ED-ED10674; E, F, Lygistorrhina mitarakensis n. sp., holotype MNHN-ED-ED10691; A, C, E, dorsal view; B, D, F, ventral view. Scale bar: 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4321234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4321234/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">4E, F</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Tergite 9 rounded at base, somewhat triangular at tip, with very long setae near apex (longer than on remainder of tergite) and a patch of sparse short setae at tip. Sternite 9 with rectangular base wider than long and square extension caudally. Gonostyli of equal width, with very dense apical and medioventral patch of setae at tip; apical tooth scoop-shaped. Aedeagal complex membranous, bell-shaped with short parallel-sided apex; gonocoxal apodemes heavily sclerotised distally; aedeagal apodeme sinusoidally curved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="600" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[130,776,1588,1837]" box="[132,272,1588,1614]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">COMPARISON</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[130,776,1588,1837]" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">
The new species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Williston, 1896)" baseAuthorityName="Williston" baseAuthorityYear="1896" class="Insecta" family="Lygistorrhinidae" genus="Probolaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="600" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[520,650,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">L. singularis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Williston" firstAuthor="Williston" pageId="9" pageNumber="600" pagination="253 - 446" refId="ref10403" refString="WILLISTON S. W. 1896. - On the Diptera of St. Vincent (West Indies). Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1896: 253 - 446, pl. VIII-XIV." type="journal article" year="1896">Williston, 1896</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
but differs by (character status in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Williston" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[559,683,1650,1676]" class="Insecta" family="Lygistorrhinidae" genus="Probolaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="600" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[559,683,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">L. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
given in brackets): flagellomeres longer (0.7-1.3× as long as wide); Costa shorter, not extending half the distance between R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[674,684,1727,1744]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">5</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[765,775,1727,1744]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">1</subScript>
(extending); M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[286,315,1759,1776]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="600">3+4</subScript>
curved anteriorly (posteriorly); fore basitarsus shorter than fore tibia (longer); abdominal segment 5 with pale apical band (completely brown).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
